## Conclusion

Improving access to mental health care in the United States requires a multifaceted approach combining technological innovation, integrated care delivery, supportive policy reforms, workforce development, and financial accessibility. Telepsychiatry and integrated care models like the Collaborative Care Model offer scalable, evidence-based solutions to extend care to underserved populations. Policy initiatives such as Medicaid expansion and the ACA have demonstrably increased insurance coverage and access, though gaps remain. Addressing workforce shortages through task-shifting and digital tools is critical to meeting demand. Finally, financial barriers must be mitigated to ensure equitable access. Sustained commitment to these strategies, informed by ongoing research and tailored to community needs, is essential to closing the mental health care access gap.

